1
00:00:00,993 --> 00:00:30,054
Namo tassa bhagavato harahato samma sambuddhassa Namo tassa bhagavato harahato samma sambuddhassa Namo tassa bhagavato harahato samma sambuddhassa Homage to the Buddha, the Blessed Noble

2
00:00:30,288 --> 00:00:33,411
and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:33,432 --> 00:00:44,807
Yes, listening to the Dharma, you know, it's, how can we say, it's, I mean, how would you behave in front of the Queen?

4
00:00:44,828 --> 00:00:45,689
I don't answer that.

5
00:00:48,792 --> 00:00:53,259
So, generally speaking, one has to adopt a proper posture.

6
00:00:53,719 --> 00:00:59,787
So, if you want to actually arrest from your sitting, bring a chair in, not a problem, you know.

7
00:01:04,527 --> 00:01:26,855
I just thought tonight to really just range around the Buddha's teachings, just framing it around the Four Noble Truths and try and make a link for you between what you're actually doing here and practice in daily life, make that as clear as possible.

8
00:01:28,674 --> 00:01:34,123
In the Buddha's life, you see, he begins as an ordinary person.

9
00:01:34,144 --> 00:01:38,310
I mean, he belongs to the ruling caste, the Kshatriya.

10
00:01:39,451 --> 00:01:50,048
His father's a local governor, a local king or something, a local potentate of a particular tribe, the Sakyas, just south of Nepal.

11
00:01:51,230 --> 00:01:54,936
And he would have been tutored to be a warrior, basically.

12
00:01:57,548 --> 00:02:13,943
And in his mid-twenties he goes through what you might call an identity crisis which manifests as recognising that youth is over and ahead of him is sickness, old age and death.

13
00:02:16,385 --> 00:02:24,373
And mythically it's put that he's out riding and he sees these particular people and each time he asks, what is it?

14
00:02:24,413 --> 00:02:26,795
Because he's been guarded from this sort of stuff.

15
00:02:28,126 --> 00:02:29,987
And does it happen to me?

16
00:02:30,588 --> 00:02:32,411
That's a big one.

17
00:02:32,431 --> 00:02:39,360
And he also sees an ascetic sitting under a tree, which suggests that maybe there was a way out of this suffering.

18
00:02:41,342 --> 00:02:54,318
So then he does what seems to have been a bit like the hippie movement of the 70s, what everybody was doing, which was to abandon the lay life and wander about as an ascetic.

19
00:02:57,015 --> 00:03:23,343
and he went to two teachers who both taught him how to establish these very beautiful states of mind that we call the absorption or jhana and each time he's invited to teach with them but each time he refuses because something in him has not been answered then he tries the mortification exercises eating very little all that sort of stuff and

20
00:03:23,881 --> 00:03:36,674
After about four years of that, that's as I've read anyway, they think, these things are not absolute fact, but that he did practice heavy mortification exercises, we can take for granted, he just found it was more suffering.

21
00:03:38,216 --> 00:03:43,561
So it was just more suffering, and it was unworthy, and a waste of time.

22
00:03:44,201 --> 00:03:52,469
So in his despair, he left his companions, he thought he'd gone soft, and sitting by the road, this woman comes along with a bit of

23
00:03:53,412 --> 00:04:20,449
rice pudding and sees how this bedraggled poor ascetic and instead of offering it to the god that she was supposed to be offering it to she offers it to him and it revives him but something happens he remembers this occasion in childhood where he's watching his father doing the ploughing ceremony and there's something about that memory there's something about that watching which awakens in him a possibility

24
00:04:20,529 --> 00:04:48,764
of another way of approaching his problem so the first way of getting into these jhanas was like an escape from life, from real life I mean the reality of ordinary daily life and just escape into yourself into these beautiful states the problem is you have to keep coming out and the other one was self-mortification was really the idea that the body was to blame so the fact that we feel greed is because the body feels hungry

25
00:04:48,862 --> 00:04:56,891
So if you can push down all those appetites, then you enter into these rather relaxed, beautiful states of mind.

26
00:04:57,971 --> 00:05:07,781
And those of you who've done a 10-day fast or a two-week fast know that after the first two or three days, you do enter into this very easy, happy state, really.

27
00:05:08,242 --> 00:05:11,584
And the body doesn't need food, mainly because it's eating itself.

28
00:05:14,427 --> 00:05:16,709
But it's definitely a good way to purify the body.

29
00:05:17,737 --> 00:05:32,278
But putting that aside as a practice, it's with that childlike investigation, that childlike curiosity sits under a tree and makes the break.

30
00:05:34,019 --> 00:05:39,829
He leaps from being an ordinary person to being this enlightened, fully enlightened person.

31
00:05:39,869 --> 00:05:47,119
We say self-enlightened because after trying everything that was on offer, it was his own

32
00:05:47,673 --> 00:06:16,278
experience from childhood that brought up this new way of investigating in fact probably the only way of investigating as such and that's why we say he's self-enlightened there was nobody to show him that path so he was the one who discovered it and then propagated it now once he has become awakened and he spends a couple of days two or three days probably more

33
00:06:16,798 --> 00:06:23,178
sort of working out the ramifications of it, the consequence of what he's seen, of what he's experienced, just like we do.

34
00:06:23,218 --> 00:06:25,726
We have an experience and then we think, what the heck was that about?

35
00:06:25,766 --> 00:06:26,589
See?

36
00:06:28,105 --> 00:06:32,850
He then goes in search of his, well, his first idea is, who can I teach?

37
00:06:33,670 --> 00:06:41,920
And there's a doubt in his mind when he realizes what he's actually achieved, which is so subtle, that he doesn't think anybody will really listen to him.

38
00:06:43,141 --> 00:06:54,213
He's at a loss, and that's put mythically as this god Sahampati coming down, the great god Sahampati, the great Brahma Sahampati coming down, saying that there are a few people, just a little dust in their eyes.

39
00:06:54,869 --> 00:06:57,132
And that's his reflection, you know, to try.

40
00:06:57,151 --> 00:06:59,596
And then he thought of his teachers, but they both died.

41
00:07:00,677 --> 00:07:03,401
And so his next port of call was his six companions.

42
00:07:03,540 --> 00:07:15,718
And he walks all the way from Bodh Gaya, right the way up to Varanasi, to Sarnath Path, which is about, I don't know how to guess, because I've done it, like I remember the distance, it must be a couple of hundred miles, a hundred or so miles.

43
00:07:15,737 --> 00:07:19,863
And he walks all the way up there to have a chat to these old friends.

44
00:07:20,182 --> 00:07:27,081
who at first don't particularly greet him very well, because I think he's gone soft, but then recognize something's changed.

45
00:07:27,101 --> 00:07:33,600
And as he's talking to them, it's very interesting, he says to them, have you ever heard me talk like this before?

46
00:07:34,559 --> 00:07:42,853
They've had chats about the Dhamma, they've had hundreds of talks and chats towards each other and met many teachers and they know him.

47
00:07:42,892 --> 00:07:50,846
And he asks them after a while, after he's began to explain the path, he says, have you ever heard me speak like this before?

48
00:07:52,608 --> 00:08:01,343
And it was after the first couple of talks that these ascetics, these old companions, also made these insights.

49
00:08:02,706 --> 00:08:15,269
Now, the important thing about the Buddha is that he's not only the founder of this particular spiritual tradition and an exemplar, he's also the archetype.

50
00:08:15,290 --> 00:08:20,259
Everybody who follows this path follows the Buddha's path, follows in his footsteps.

51
00:08:20,779 --> 00:08:26,470
There has to be a point in our lives when we reflect and think, well, what's all this about?

52
00:08:27,259 --> 00:08:28,060
We wouldn't be here.

53
00:08:28,422 --> 00:08:33,629
None of us would be here at all if we hadn't woken up one morning and thought, what am I doing here?

54
00:08:33,649 --> 00:08:34,130
Who am I?

55
00:08:34,150 --> 00:08:34,751
What am I doing here?

56
00:08:34,772 --> 00:08:35,413
What's this about?

57
00:08:36,534 --> 00:08:39,620
So there's that questioning about the purpose of life.

58
00:08:41,503 --> 00:08:45,929
And the training is this process of self-investigation.

59
00:08:46,129 --> 00:08:47,513
Very simple.

60
00:08:47,533 --> 00:08:48,975
The investigation isn't out there.

61
00:08:49,014 --> 00:08:52,259
The answer doesn't lie out there for our internal problems.

62
00:08:52,340 --> 00:08:53,402
It lies within us.

63
00:08:54,731 --> 00:08:58,918
and that once we begin to practice, it affects the way we are.

64
00:09:00,160 --> 00:09:18,410
Now, after he had made this great effort, awakened to the truth, the Dharma, as we say, he then goes out, he re-engages in life, he re-engages, he doesn't sit there under the tree feeling happy for himself.

65
00:09:18,592 --> 00:09:21,716
you know, and telling people to get on with it, you know, get on with it.

66
00:09:21,735 --> 00:09:24,678
I just want to be left alone, please.

67
00:09:24,698 --> 00:09:25,340
Leave me alone.

68
00:09:26,260 --> 00:09:27,822
Not available, sign, you know.

69
00:09:28,322 --> 00:09:32,927
Far from it, he's out there and for the rest of his life, 45 years, he's tramping up and down.

70
00:09:33,027 --> 00:09:34,849
And it's not so easy.

71
00:09:35,110 --> 00:09:45,580
I mean, at the beginning, he seems to gather people around him who are fervent, probably already existing ascetics, who've known him for years because he's been around, you know.

72
00:09:45,695 --> 00:10:03,315
and who hear about him two of the great ones of course were his companions Sariputta and Moggallana both of whom had been ascetics they were Brahmins by caste been ascetics for quite some time and not satisfied with their teacher had gone wandering

73
00:10:03,294 --> 00:10:13,188
And it was Sariputta who met Asaji, who was one of the companions, he said, you know, he said, you look bright, and you look, he says, yes, he said, you know, who's your teacher?

74
00:10:13,208 --> 00:10:14,250
He said, yeah, what does he teach?

75
00:10:14,289 --> 00:10:27,609
He teaches, for whatever arises, let me get this right now, for whatever arises, there is a cause, and there's a cause for whatever passes away, something like that.

76
00:10:27,629 --> 00:10:29,792
We chant it in the morning, I should know it really.

77
00:10:30,227 --> 00:10:30,989
It's the first one.

78
00:10:31,529 --> 00:10:42,163
Anyway, that aside, Sariputta, his curiosity is awakened and he goes to see the Buddha and eventually becomes his primary disciple.

79
00:10:42,222 --> 00:10:46,908
He's the one who is credited to understand the Dharma, second only to the Buddha.

80
00:10:47,349 --> 00:10:49,731
He was given the title of General of the Dharma.

81
00:10:50,754 --> 00:10:53,277
His companion, Moggallana, is the magic guy.

82
00:10:53,297 --> 00:10:55,318
He's the one who can do all these magical tricks.

83
00:10:55,940 --> 00:10:59,104
And he becomes the patron saint, you might say, of the Mahayana tradition.

84
00:11:01,835 --> 00:11:07,181
Just as a little aside, Moggallana has a big problem with sloth and torpor.

85
00:11:08,201 --> 00:11:13,888
And he asks the Buddha what to do, and the Buddha gives him 11 things that he can do before he sleeps.

86
00:11:14,969 --> 00:11:22,778
He's got to rub his eyes, rub his legs, open his eyes, stand up, chant, do all sorts of things.

87
00:11:23,217 --> 00:11:29,445
And only after 11 different things, I think it's 11, he can say to himself, I am tired, I will have a rest.

88
00:11:31,062 --> 00:11:34,788
Now he becomes fully liberated in one week, for heaven's sake.

89
00:11:35,889 --> 00:11:36,870
It kind of lasted that long.

90
00:11:37,532 --> 00:11:44,383
Sariputta, who didn't ask any questions, had just got the basic grip of the practice and went off investigating.

91
00:11:44,524 --> 00:11:47,989
It took him two weeks.

92
00:11:48,009 --> 00:11:51,916
Well, there's something in that, I think.

93
00:11:52,716 --> 00:11:58,385
The intellectual person is often at a disadvantage because he just can't get beyond the thinking mind.

94
00:12:00,052 --> 00:12:12,471
So anyway, the Buddha, the reason I tell this story is to show that the Buddha's life is the exemplum, the archetype, and it happens to us in small stages.

95
00:12:12,650 --> 00:12:19,360
We go on retreat, we clear some things up, we get little insights about things, but then we've got to go back, we've got to re-engage.

96
00:12:22,846 --> 00:12:28,794
And in time, not immediately, in time he formulated these Four Noble Truths.

97
00:12:30,158 --> 00:12:34,605
And these Four Noble Truths form the basis of all forms of Buddhism.

98
00:12:34,625 --> 00:12:38,471
If a Buddhism doesn't have the Four Noble Truths, it's simply not Buddhism.

99
00:12:39,212 --> 00:12:52,195
Because although there are in time doctrinal differences, they tend to be not concerned with the root of the teaching, which is this Four Noble Truths.

100
00:12:52,235 --> 00:12:55,760
They tend to be concerned with the nature of consciousness and things like that.

101
00:12:57,192 --> 00:13:05,030
So the first noble truth is stated very clearly, it's just the truth of suffering, the truth of dukkha, the truth of unsatisfactoriness.

102
00:13:05,591 --> 00:13:13,951
And this dukkha is very hard to translate because it includes the joy that we get from pleasures and the happinesses of life.

103
00:13:15,028 --> 00:13:32,535
So it's a word which catches any form of discontent to the most horrific anguish and despair possible to humankind, dependent on pleasure or direct painful suffering.

104
00:13:32,556 --> 00:13:35,399
It's the whole gamut of human misery.

105
00:13:35,379 --> 00:13:37,583
See?

106
00:13:37,783 --> 00:13:40,830
And it's translated in various ways.

107
00:13:40,909 --> 00:13:43,033
Unsatisfactoriness, lack.

108
00:13:43,234 --> 00:13:45,577
Somebody translates it as a lack.

109
00:13:45,597 --> 00:13:50,486
It used to be translated as suffering, but that's too narrow a word, really.

110
00:13:51,057 --> 00:13:55,681
And he points to three reasons as to where this suffering and how it arises.

111
00:13:55,841 --> 00:13:57,423
And that's these three characteristics.

112
00:13:58,183 --> 00:14:07,893
It's the fact that things arise and pass away that makes it impossible for us to hold a moment of time to stop the world and say, I'm happy now, don't move.

113
00:14:09,855 --> 00:14:10,495
It just doesn't work.

114
00:14:10,635 --> 00:14:11,255
You can't do it.

115
00:14:12,398 --> 00:14:18,482
And even when you've had a great party and foolishly people say, we must have another one.

116
00:14:19,024 --> 00:14:20,085
No, no, no.

117
00:14:20,960 --> 00:14:22,522
I'm a real damp squid, you know.

118
00:14:24,325 --> 00:14:25,667
So, and that's what we do.

119
00:14:25,687 --> 00:14:26,749
We try to hold on to it.

120
00:14:26,769 --> 00:14:27,350
That's what we're doing.

121
00:14:27,370 --> 00:14:31,255
We hold on to what gives us pleasure.

122
00:14:31,876 --> 00:14:34,821
And that grip, that's the cramp, you see.

123
00:14:34,841 --> 00:14:39,889
And as we've been discussing throughout the week, it has its consequences, its aftermath.

124
00:14:39,908 --> 00:14:45,076
It's like, you know, it has its diseases that come afterwards, you know.

125
00:14:45,057 --> 00:14:51,644
the sense of addiction to something, you know, a compulsiveness about something.

126
00:14:51,663 --> 00:14:55,587
Even silly things like tea and toast, for heaven's sake, can cause enormous misery.

127
00:14:56,349 --> 00:14:59,392
Can't they?

128
00:15:00,032 --> 00:15:00,452
Absolutely.

129
00:15:01,433 --> 00:15:11,663
And the grief at loss, which gets worse and worse and worse the more you're attached to objects and especially people.

130
00:15:11,823 --> 00:15:13,326
A lot of grief, my heavens.

131
00:15:13,745 --> 00:15:16,110
And frustration if you don't get what you want.

132
00:15:16,432 --> 00:15:18,476
Especially if a person doesn't do what you want.

133
00:15:18,496 --> 00:15:19,379
That's very frustrating.

134
00:15:21,464 --> 00:15:24,150
And of course this constant underlying anxiety.

135
00:15:24,731 --> 00:15:28,682
And that's of course the basis, the basic position of the self.

136
00:15:29,590 --> 00:15:31,634
The self knows it's going to destruct.

137
00:15:32,154 --> 00:15:34,359
It knows death's up there somewhere, ahead of it.

138
00:15:34,840 --> 00:15:43,236
Therefore, underneath everything that we are experiencing, there lies this anxiety, whether we're aware of it or not.

139
00:15:43,898 --> 00:15:49,809
And it surfaces when something horrible happens to us, or nearly happens to us.

140
00:15:50,735 --> 00:15:53,057
So anxiety is just part and parcel.

141
00:15:53,076 --> 00:15:59,705
We talk about this age being the age of anxiety, but that's because this age does push us to the edge of it.

142
00:16:01,385 --> 00:16:09,674
I mean, we've become such sophisticated culture, a sophisticated civilization that we don't know what we'd do if the electricity went.

143
00:16:10,576 --> 00:16:14,701
I mean, if you go to New Guinea and live with a tribe, they don't have electricity.

144
00:16:14,721 --> 00:16:15,721
They live perfectly well.

145
00:16:15,741 --> 00:16:18,884
But for us, it's like the end of the world if electricity goes off.

146
00:16:18,982 --> 00:16:20,687
We become soft in that sense.

147
00:16:20,888 --> 00:16:29,272
We become dependent entirely upon a standard of living which is fragile.

148
00:16:29,292 --> 00:16:30,134
Fragile, really.

149
00:16:30,796 --> 00:16:32,200
And that's what we're coming to learn, aren't we?

150
00:16:33,985 --> 00:16:49,750
so these emotions these mental states all hang around this idea of pleasure and the reason we go to pleasure is because at least at that point you know we feel happy you know I scream

151
00:16:49,730 --> 00:16:51,231
makes you happy is great.

152
00:16:52,433 --> 00:16:56,902
Anything that lifts us out of the misery of life is great.

153
00:16:57,001 --> 00:16:58,043
And of course, why not?

154
00:16:58,264 --> 00:16:59,927
You go for it.

155
00:16:59,947 --> 00:17:03,192
And that would be the general culture of a consumerist society.

156
00:17:03,231 --> 00:17:04,094
It plays on that.

157
00:17:04,413 --> 00:17:11,586
It plays on the fact that pleasant things, pleasant experiences make you happy.

158
00:17:12,612 --> 00:17:21,340
And at the extreme level, you get these extreme sports where the person puts themselves in a position where they're right there in the moment.

159
00:17:21,421 --> 00:17:24,864
You know, you miss the moment, you fall off the cliff or your canoe goes under or something.

160
00:17:25,464 --> 00:17:35,914
And to live at that level of absolute moment to moment is quite a breathtaking thing as long as you don't think you are going to die.

161
00:17:36,935 --> 00:17:37,876
You wouldn't do it otherwise.

162
00:17:40,844 --> 00:17:43,886
But of course, that's one heck of a way to live.

163
00:17:43,926 --> 00:17:49,592
I presume you die of heart attack in your mid-life, trying to live at that level of intensity.

164
00:17:50,153 --> 00:17:56,858
But that's why they do it, because at that intense level, there's a real being alive, being aware.

165
00:17:57,180 --> 00:18:00,643
And what we're trying to do is to get to that without extreme sports.

166
00:18:00,903 --> 00:18:07,189
We don't have to be an extreme sport person to be absolutely alive in this present moment.

167
00:18:11,911 --> 00:18:16,842
And apart from this impermanence,

168
00:18:18,576 --> 00:18:43,026
When we actually see impermanence, when we begin to grasp impermanence, when it begins to sink into the heart, when it begins to be digested at the level deep within the heart, at that attitudinal level, then we begin to see the truth of the Buddha's phrase, there is nothing in this world worth holding on to.

169
00:18:44,448 --> 00:18:47,030
There's nothing in this world worth holding on to.

170
00:18:51,532 --> 00:18:55,240
You keep repeating that, you keep repeating that until it sort of sinks in.

171
00:18:55,480 --> 00:19:03,416
And as it sinks in, there's all sorts of things can come up because there are so many things we do hold on to.

172
00:19:06,443 --> 00:19:10,571
Our spouses, our partners, our children.

173
00:19:11,142 --> 00:19:38,432
our parents, there's a whole load of relationships that we have which we're deeply entwined and when these people disappear one way or the other through death or whatever it just leaves this sort of gaping wound doesn't it in the heart he's left there with this gaping wound and what can you do you see now we make the mistake of thinking that this is love but in fact

174
00:19:39,559 --> 00:19:43,586
It's only because of that self-definition, who I am.

175
00:19:43,606 --> 00:19:46,551
I am somebody's spouse.

176
00:19:46,711 --> 00:19:47,673
I am somebody's spouse.

177
00:19:47,794 --> 00:19:50,478
I am, you see, I am this person's mother, father.

178
00:19:51,180 --> 00:19:53,723
Those definitions of I am, you see.

179
00:19:54,525 --> 00:19:57,450
Have you read Kahlil Gibran?

180
00:19:58,240 --> 00:20:00,222
That beautiful Lebanese poet.

181
00:20:01,325 --> 00:20:06,493
Well, you know, he talks about, just in this one case, that children don't belong to you, they come through you.

182
00:20:06,535 --> 00:20:09,720
They come by way of you into the world and whatnot, you know.

183
00:20:10,441 --> 00:20:13,666
And that's a lovely way to sort of see our relationships.

184
00:20:15,217 --> 00:20:17,398
So that's what seeing impermanence does.

185
00:20:17,459 --> 00:20:27,569
It releases us from the suffering of that grasping nature we have, which is deep within us because it's to do with me, to do with my self-definition.

186
00:20:27,589 --> 00:20:35,278
It's like when on a level of the body itself we define ourselves by this body we have now.

187
00:20:36,000 --> 00:20:40,144
So if by accident we lose our sight, it's a catastrophe for us.

188
00:20:42,115 --> 00:20:49,727
If you lose a part of your legs, if you have an accident on the road and you become a paraplegic, it's like the world disappears for you.

189
00:20:49,787 --> 00:20:50,568
Who am I now?

190
00:20:51,810 --> 00:21:02,587
We'd recently, didn't we, that young lad who got injured in the rugby thing and his parents finally took him to Switzerland.

191
00:21:04,103 --> 00:21:05,465
he'd lost his reason for being.

192
00:21:06,047 --> 00:21:06,808
Completely lost it.

193
00:21:06,970 --> 00:21:10,718
And I'm sure everybody tried to give him good reasons, but he just couldn't find it.

194
00:21:11,359 --> 00:21:17,051
Because he defined himself as, I am an active sports person and I win, you know, and I score tries.

195
00:21:17,974 --> 00:21:22,585
You know, it's like, and these definitions that we have, they're very, you know, they go very deep.

196
00:21:23,492 --> 00:21:31,625
And so when something happens to us which drags that away, which pulls us out from that self-definition, it's a catastrophe.

197
00:21:31,925 --> 00:21:32,646
Losing your job.

198
00:21:33,167 --> 00:21:43,022
I mean losing your job is hard enough, it's painful enough in terms of your economic situation and all that, but it's even worse when you've defined yourself as I am.

199
00:21:44,144 --> 00:21:50,934
Just been listening now to the news of this nurse who leads a panorama program about looking after the elderly.

200
00:21:51,454 --> 00:21:53,037
And they filmed it in a hospital.

201
00:21:53,116 --> 00:21:55,440
Did anybody see that program?

202
00:21:55,460 --> 00:21:56,060
Yeah.

203
00:21:56,080 --> 00:22:05,653
Well, anyway, she's been struck off the list of nurses on the grounds that she didn't put the privacy of the patients first.

204
00:22:06,233 --> 00:22:10,199
But from her point of view, of course, she'd been complaining about the situation.

205
00:22:10,798 --> 00:22:11,881
Nobody was listening to her.

206
00:22:12,422 --> 00:22:16,787
And so she went undercover with the Panorama team.

207
00:22:17,122 --> 00:22:21,859
And you can hear from her voice that she's only just heard, I think, today sometime.

208
00:22:21,880 --> 00:22:26,096
She's in this huge state of shock because, like, what's she going to do now, you know?

209
00:22:26,116 --> 00:22:28,566
She's been kicked out of her own profession.

210
00:22:31,313 --> 00:23:01,101
so that sense of that sense of impermanence you see rebounds back on this sense of self and that's the other characteristic the other characteristic is this is this idea that things are compounded a whole entire but in fact whatever we investigate in our lives whether it's what we do whether it's the body whether it's the the mechanisms of the mind the emotional life and all that it's all

211
00:23:01,080 --> 00:23:12,914
it's all bits and pieces, it's all compounded bits and pieces, which, you know, we do have the capacity to hold it all together into a concept of me, but then we believe that that's what I am, which is very different.

212
00:23:13,675 --> 00:23:21,124
I mean, the Buddha didn't go schizophrenic when he became, you know, fully liberated, he didn't sort of split up into pieces and collapse into pieces.

213
00:23:21,545 --> 00:23:24,387
In fact, if anything, he became very charismatic.

214
00:23:24,570 --> 00:23:41,382
so there was coming out of him this entire personage which people met obviously very impressive but he wasn't fooled by that he didn't think I am this guru or something

215
00:23:41,362 --> 00:23:48,409
So something about our relationship to the way we are, to how we experience ourselves, is to do with this self.

216
00:23:48,848 --> 00:23:52,231
And remember that the Buddha is not saying there is no self.

217
00:23:52,511 --> 00:23:54,334
He doesn't go into metaphysics.

218
00:23:54,354 --> 00:23:58,897
He just says, look, ask the question, who am I?

219
00:23:59,098 --> 00:23:59,898
Who do you think you are?

220
00:24:00,500 --> 00:24:08,027
And then look inward and see if there's anything there which holds, which sustains, which you can say, oh, well, this is me.

221
00:24:08,934 --> 00:24:09,154
See?

222
00:24:09,915 --> 00:24:13,378
And that's the technique of not me, not mine.

223
00:24:13,778 --> 00:24:14,079
See?

224
00:24:14,099 --> 00:24:15,240
Not me, not mine.

225
00:24:15,641 --> 00:24:19,144
And that that I'm looking at is not a self.

226
00:24:19,163 --> 00:24:26,631
So, you know, like the pain in my knee definitely feels like me, but when I look at it and distance from it, it's just there is a pain in the knee.

227
00:24:27,352 --> 00:24:34,397
And the pain in the knee is not substantial either, because I can go into it and it dissolves into all sorts of little bits and feelings.

228
00:24:35,398 --> 00:24:38,622
Not only that, I haven't a clue what's happening at the chemical level anyway.

229
00:24:38,922 --> 00:24:42,346
or the electrical level, the nerve level.

230
00:24:43,607 --> 00:24:55,541
There's a whole load of stuff that the self in terms of I seems to take for granted, but when it actually looks into things, it discovers it actually knows nothing.

231
00:24:56,323 --> 00:24:57,644
It knows very little about the body.

232
00:24:58,365 --> 00:24:59,426
We know it as a science.

233
00:24:59,807 --> 00:25:04,894
People tell us that when we breathe, oxygen comes in and carbon dioxide goes out.

234
00:25:04,933 --> 00:25:06,516
Well, who's experienced that?

235
00:25:06,817 --> 00:25:08,060
I don't believe a word of it, frankly.

236
00:25:11,653 --> 00:25:12,615
I'd have to prove it to me.

237
00:25:12,655 --> 00:25:17,290
Put a plastic bag over my head.

238
00:25:17,310 --> 00:25:19,037
If I'm dead in four minutes, they were right.

239
00:25:21,093 --> 00:25:25,040
So it's a case of, you know, what do we know?

240
00:25:25,080 --> 00:25:26,964
What do we really, really know?

241
00:25:26,984 --> 00:25:32,375
And all we're left with is our basic experience through the senses.

242
00:25:32,616 --> 00:25:33,458
That's what we're left with.

243
00:25:33,838 --> 00:25:42,155
And then we have to begin to investigate as to whether this is actually something real, whether it's not also made up.

244
00:25:44,481 --> 00:25:58,969
Now because of these two positions of I am and the fact that everything I am seems to be changing it manifests in the characteristic of suffering which is the third one.

245
00:25:59,088 --> 00:26:03,958
It's usually rated second but I'm doing it this way.

246
00:26:05,473 --> 00:26:16,664
Now in the dependent origination, you see, that suffering comes in as thirst, desire, wanting for this sort of happiness in a wrong way

247
00:26:17,101 --> 00:26:37,708
and what the Buddha points to in the second noble truth is that this is the cause of suffering so this is the manifest cause of suffering the underlying cause of suffering is this ignorance is this delusion about who we are and about continuity and all that business but it manifests as desire

248
00:26:38,498 --> 00:27:03,071
and so any time we find ourselves desiring something in that compulsive way and we know that it's a wrong desire because if it's not satisfied we feel unhappy for it in one way or the other as soon as we see desire we know that this is a manifestation of this essential delusion as to who I am and it becomes really clear to you

249
00:27:03,710 --> 00:27:03,970
You see?

250
00:27:04,211 --> 00:27:09,117
So he's not pointing at some metaphysical thing about not-self, you know, I am not-self.

251
00:27:10,839 --> 00:27:20,314
There was, my old teacher, he used to say, he met this fellow in India, this Indian monk, who was into not-self, I am not a person, I am not a thing.

252
00:27:20,934 --> 00:27:32,551
And he had an elephant, and he didn't like to use the word me or mine, so he would say, he would talk to, say to my teacher, he would say, you're elephant.

253
00:27:33,038 --> 00:27:38,769
He always put everything in the yours or his.

254
00:27:38,788 --> 00:27:39,892
He wouldn't use me or mine.

255
00:27:40,512 --> 00:27:46,003
It's all real crazy stuff, actually.

256
00:27:46,023 --> 00:27:48,769
It's a very strange thing.

257
00:27:49,458 --> 00:28:04,664
So this second noble truth of desire, the cause of suffering, the cause of suffering, makes it very simple for us actually, because every time we can feel a lack, every time we can feel a yearning,

258
00:28:04,644 --> 00:28:06,788
you know, which comes up in all sorts of ways.

259
00:28:06,847 --> 00:28:19,787
It's not just yearning for food and money, loneliness, a sense of yearning, nostalgia, there's a whole range of these sort of, you know, desires that come up into the mind.

260
00:28:20,567 --> 00:28:27,798
And if we're sharp enough, if we stay at this level of awareness, we can see it, we can see it, and we can name it.

261
00:28:27,959 --> 00:28:34,567
That's one of the better points of noting, you're straight on it, you say, that's wrong desire.

262
00:28:35,576 --> 00:28:45,795
And you see, that noting, that labelling of it, that actual recognition of it, does allow us a moment of reflection.

263
00:28:46,675 --> 00:28:50,864
We might not, we might just say, to hell with it, I'll have that piece of toast anyway.

264
00:28:50,884 --> 00:28:53,327
But it does allow us a moment of reflection.

265
00:28:54,871 --> 00:28:57,095
And then we realise this importance of intention.

266
00:28:58,096 --> 00:28:58,497
And...

267
00:29:00,146 --> 00:29:28,045
we've got a choice, that's the point of choice we call it a choice because there are two roads open to us we can either indulge it and keep going down the road towards suffering or we can let go of it and move towards the road of liberation but in a more realistic sense once we know where the path is there isn't a choice you know I mean really we ought to do that which is going to lead us out of suffering

268
00:29:28,395 --> 00:29:35,326
and to sort of build up the commitment to that particular path.

269
00:29:39,112 --> 00:29:40,253
So that's his second noble truth.

270
00:29:40,273 --> 00:29:45,721
Now the third one, you see, is a very clear, direct statement.

271
00:29:45,922 --> 00:29:47,964
There is an end to suffering.

272
00:29:48,105 --> 00:29:49,627
He doesn't use the word nibbana.

273
00:29:50,388 --> 00:29:50,568
See?

274
00:29:50,809 --> 00:29:53,693
His whole teaching is about suffering and the end of suffering.

275
00:29:53,933 --> 00:29:57,660
I'm using suffering now with that huge sort of gamut of understanding.

276
00:29:58,635 --> 00:30:27,343
when he reduces his stuff he says all I teach is dukkha and dukkha nirodha in the pālī it's three words he reduces his whole teaching to three words dukkha, dukkha nirodha suffering, unsatisfactoriness, discontent and the end of that so the third noble truth is not phrased there is this mythical place called Nibbāna you know this Shangri-lā which you can head towards you know east of Birmingham

277
00:30:28,842 --> 00:30:56,907
no West sorry West we're here so no it's not that at all he says he says there is an end to suffering that's just a great straightforward you know statement and that's it and one of the one of the words that he uses in the definition in the in the sort of approach to this is Nibbida which is weariness weariness

278
00:30:58,626 --> 00:31:00,109
That's not being fed up.

279
00:31:00,932 --> 00:31:01,854
That's not being bored.

280
00:31:02,896 --> 00:31:07,386
Weariness, it comes to you when, in a sense, you've had enough.

281
00:31:08,890 --> 00:31:13,180
Very old people sometimes just die just because they just had enough.

282
00:31:14,182 --> 00:31:15,084
You know, they just let go.

283
00:31:15,164 --> 00:31:16,247
They've had enough.

284
00:31:16,480 --> 00:31:28,477
One example I like to use is when little children, so you know, you've got a four or five year old and they want to play tiddly drinks or snakes and ladders, you know, and you say, oh yeah, come on, let's play, you know.

285
00:31:28,497 --> 00:31:41,256
So you have a great one game and then they say, let's have another one, you see, and you say, well, just a minute, I've got, I get off, you know, I've played snakes and ladders once with a kid and that's about it.

286
00:31:44,694 --> 00:31:48,740
So it's that sort of weariness, one wearies of things.

287
00:31:50,321 --> 00:31:55,169
And that's a good sign, that's a spiritual sign, that's a spiritual indicator to the person.

288
00:31:55,749 --> 00:32:04,881
It's not that they are losing their desire to live or anything like that, it's just that that way of life no longer attracts.

289
00:32:05,501 --> 00:32:14,490
And if we think about the stages of sainthood, there are four paths and fruits, there are four levels.

290
00:32:14,852 --> 00:32:17,233
The third level is known as non-returner.

291
00:32:17,733 --> 00:32:26,343
Now, you can think of that in this sort of traditional Buddhist way, that when they die they don't come back to this realm.

292
00:32:26,743 --> 00:32:34,951
But in terms of the spiritual life, what it's saying is there is nothing in this world which attracts them anymore.

293
00:32:34,932 --> 00:32:41,406
They're living in this world where attachment is not possible to the sensual life because they've become weary of it.

294
00:32:42,229 --> 00:32:44,795
They've gone beyond seeking that sort of happiness.

295
00:32:45,055 --> 00:32:48,242
Which doesn't mean they don't eat and drink and do all the other things.

296
00:32:48,603 --> 00:32:51,490
It's just that they're no longer attached to it as a form of happiness.

297
00:33:02,236 --> 00:33:09,157
When they say of somebody who's achieved the end, there's a lovely phrase of, they've laid down the burden.

298
00:33:09,178 --> 00:33:10,240
I really like that phrase.

299
00:33:12,126 --> 00:33:14,153
They have laid down the burden.

300
00:33:16,494 --> 00:33:18,877
And then, of course, he lays out the path.

301
00:33:19,298 --> 00:33:26,406
And this four things, the way he laid it out, by the way, was the way that doctors in those times worked with diseases.

302
00:33:26,527 --> 00:33:37,500
The disease was mentioned, was spoken, what the disease was, what was the cause of the disease, what was the prognosis, and what was the medicine to be used for the end of the disease.

303
00:33:37,559 --> 00:33:46,349
So he very much sees himself as a doctor of the mind, as a psychotherapist or a psychiatrist or something.

304
00:33:46,786 --> 00:34:10,025
and he sees himself in that role because he's about suffering and then we've got these the Eightfold Path which he delineates and it starts off with this Right Understanding and this Right Understanding is exactly what we've been talking about it's beginning to understand the three characteristics mainly that's what it's about

305
00:34:10,005 --> 00:34:23,911
And included in that three characteristics, remember, is this whole business of suffering, the cause of desire being the cause, and therein lies all that teaching about the dependent origination that we chant in the morning.

306
00:34:23,931 --> 00:34:28,099
And maybe there'll be time to look into that tomorrow.

307
00:34:29,581 --> 00:34:48,753
so this right understanding begins with first of all what you hear and then what you think for yourself and then what you yourself experience through the teaching so it becomes a deeper understanding of knowledge until it becomes your own personal experience

308
00:34:48,733 --> 00:35:10,641
and that's when it has obviously a greater effect but if it stays only at that sort of level of understanding and thinking it never really drops, it never really moves into the attitudinal base which is where your will lies and the will expresses itself through the heart

309
00:35:10,722 --> 00:35:14,025
And how does that attitudinal base express itself?

310
00:35:14,967 --> 00:35:17,110
It's always the three same examples.

311
00:35:17,510 --> 00:35:20,813
It's always from selfishness to generosity.

312
00:35:21,454 --> 00:35:24,818
So once you lose the self, you're not always feeding into the self.

313
00:35:25,579 --> 00:35:29,023
The self, remember, this selfishness is not to be confused with self-care.

314
00:35:29,443 --> 00:35:30,065
One has to eat.

315
00:35:31,567 --> 00:35:35,952
But whether it has to be beef stroganoff every night is another matter.

316
00:35:36,391 --> 00:35:38,534
Or a cheesecake.

317
00:35:39,679 --> 00:35:41,202
Yes, cheesecake.

318
00:35:41,222 --> 00:35:56,574
So it's a case of recognizing that there's a shift in our attitude, and that's another telltale to the meditator, that they're moving spiritually because their attitudes change, the way they're actually behaving changes.

319
00:35:56,824 --> 00:36:03,572
There's a lovely scene in the scriptures of three fully enlightened monks living together.

320
00:36:04,152 --> 00:36:05,673
And they're known as the Anurudas.

321
00:36:05,693 --> 00:36:10,579
They have three separate names, but the Buddha approached them as the Anurudas because that was the name of the chief monk.

322
00:36:10,900 --> 00:36:14,342
And he asks them, how do you live so peacefully together?

323
00:36:15,885 --> 00:36:24,333
And the reply is, well, I say to myself, what if I put aside what I want to do and do what the others want to do?

324
00:36:27,014 --> 00:36:28,378
Have you ever tried that?

325
00:36:28,398 --> 00:36:32,989
What if I put aside what I want to do and do what the others want to do?

326
00:36:33,230 --> 00:36:35,576
Now, frankly, that only works if the others are saying the same thing.

327
00:36:37,641 --> 00:36:39,706
You can tend to be abused.

328
00:36:42,032 --> 00:36:44,775
So you have to bring a bit of noose to this practice, you know.

329
00:36:45,797 --> 00:36:49,860
But they live peacefully by being open to what the other person wanted to do.

330
00:36:49,900 --> 00:36:51,443
And then obviously there was some discussion.

331
00:36:52,324 --> 00:36:56,047
And this other lovely thing that he says, he says they go off an arm's round.

332
00:36:56,467 --> 00:36:59,351
Whoever comes back first sets up the table.

333
00:36:59,451 --> 00:37:03,434
So it's not, you know, well, you said you were going to do it and I was waiting for you.

334
00:37:05,697 --> 00:37:11,262
You know, it's like there was a cup that needs to be washed and everybody's waiting for somebody else to do it.

335
00:37:15,192 --> 00:37:20,708
So it's a case of they came back and it had the table and the preparation for the meal.

336
00:37:20,728 --> 00:37:23,195
And then whoever was last cleaned up.

337
00:37:23,215 --> 00:37:27,126
Obviously, if you didn't want to be last, you had to be quicker.

338
00:37:32,083 --> 00:37:38,753
So this expresses itself through this lack of selfishness and a movement towards generosity.

339
00:37:39,333 --> 00:37:46,864
And remember that generosity demands you lose something that you are treasuring, that you thought you would use for yourself.

340
00:37:47,385 --> 00:37:52,793
You're giving away some time, some time of your life for the benefit of somebody else.

341
00:37:53,751 --> 00:38:03,945
Or you're giving away some wealth which you've spent time earning, which you had demarked for this special treat, and you're giving it away for somebody else.

342
00:38:04,467 --> 00:38:09,474
So even through the act of generosity, there's a loss of self.

343
00:38:09,554 --> 00:38:19,067
Every time we do it with a proper, clean, full-hearted purpose for the benefit of the other, we're undermining the self.

344
00:38:19,199 --> 00:38:20,244
We're undermining the self.

345
00:38:20,465 --> 00:38:25,512
And at the most dramatic of that is of course when somebody gives their life away for another.

346
00:38:26,253 --> 00:38:31,358
I went to Auschwitz a couple of years last year.

347
00:38:32,257 --> 00:38:32,759
Last year.

348
00:38:33,420 --> 00:38:36,302
And just amazing, really.

349
00:38:36,422 --> 00:38:41,347
But in the context that we're speaking of, there's a particular Catholic priest, Father Maximilian.

350
00:38:42,248 --> 00:38:53,677
And the SS there decided to starve to death ten men because of some parties and activity.

351
00:38:53,775 --> 00:38:57,780
And one of them was crying, you know, he had a wife and children, all this sort of stuff.

352
00:38:57,800 --> 00:39:00,543
So Maximilian stood forth and said he'd take his place.

353
00:39:00,884 --> 00:39:01,844
And they allowed him to do that.

354
00:39:02,206 --> 00:39:04,728
And they just shut them up in this room until they died of starvation.

355
00:39:08,693 --> 00:39:09,954
So that's the greatest of all.

356
00:39:10,014 --> 00:39:11,275
No greater gift as man.

357
00:39:11,295 --> 00:39:12,077
That's Jesus, isn't it?

358
00:39:12,117 --> 00:39:14,199
No greater gift as man than to give his life for another.

359
00:39:15,101 --> 00:39:17,083
So that's how far generosity can go.

360
00:39:17,143 --> 00:39:20,246
And I mean to do that, you really mustn't think of yourself.

361
00:39:22,128 --> 00:39:22,989
Something has to go.

362
00:39:24,572 --> 00:39:29,818
And the other one is to move away from hatred towards love, towards aversion towards love.

363
00:39:31,039 --> 00:39:33,922
And that manifests our relationships to each other.

364
00:39:34,583 --> 00:39:37,686
And the third one is away from cruelty towards compassion.

365
00:39:38,567 --> 00:39:50,157
And we're not particularly talking about torturing people, but just getting our own back, a nasty word, a cutting remark, all those little ways that we diminish compassion.

366
00:39:50,981 --> 00:40:06,898
other people all that disappears and towards compassion so these are your three big ones but actually you can take any negative

367
00:40:09,291 --> 00:40:33,914
attitude and the meditation will move you towards the opposite so for instance loneliness so loneliness is you know a feeling that you know you you're not loved you're not wanted you're abandoned all that sort of stuff and it can become very self-piteous and all that but if you sit with it you see if you sit with the feeling of loneliness if you sit with that feeling of

368
00:40:33,894 --> 00:40:38,079
of being unloved and all that sort of stuff, you know, poor little me.

369
00:40:38,400 --> 00:40:42,003
When it dies away, the gift comes, you see.

370
00:40:42,043 --> 00:40:45,907
Whenever you let go of these things, there always comes up with a gift.

371
00:40:45,927 --> 00:40:47,869
But you don't know what the gift is until you let go.

372
00:40:48,130 --> 00:40:57,518
It's not like you've got an old TV and you think, well, I'll kick this out because you know which one you're going to get, the new plasma.

373
00:40:57,719 --> 00:41:00,342
It's not quite like that because you don't quite know what you're going to get.

374
00:41:00,659 --> 00:41:28,168
you have to give something up first so there you are bearing with this sense of loneliness you know which can for some people is of course a very deep profound feeling driving them towards despair and to just sit with it and when it begins to disappear you see what arises what arises solitude and solitude is to be perfectly happy just by just on one's own

375
00:41:29,161 --> 00:41:32,324
We experience it in little blitz and blobs when you've had too much of people.

376
00:41:32,945 --> 00:41:34,507
You've got to be on your own for a little while.

377
00:41:34,606 --> 00:41:36,289
But that's a poor solitude.

378
00:41:38,431 --> 00:41:41,034
To get that solitude, you've got to have lots of people around you annoying you.

379
00:41:43,257 --> 00:41:44,177
And an escape route.

380
00:41:46,101 --> 00:41:52,708
But real solitude is when you've discovered, you have engendered, you've found the love for yourself.

381
00:41:53,309 --> 00:41:55,271
You don't need anybody else to love you for heaven's sake.

382
00:41:55,291 --> 00:41:56,873
You're all right on your own, thanks very much.

383
00:41:57,916 --> 00:42:05,505
And that's the purpose of sometimes being on your own and bearing with those sorts of feelings.

384
00:42:05,527 --> 00:42:08,398
So this process,

385
00:42:09,322 --> 00:42:18,911
of understanding, changing our emotional, attitudinal base, you see, comes through the practice, but it doesn't just come through sitting here.

